Perhaps it may be thought that the differenoe between Oioero and Lucretius is not a difference of meaning as to the word religio, but a difference of feeling and judgment as regards the facts denoted by the word. Such a view would be quite consistent with the supposition that Cicero’s dialogus is intended in part as a protest against the doctrine advocated by Lucretius ; but Lucretius himself asserts more than once that his doctrine is not hostile to religiones Cicero would under- stand that word¹. In either case it seems to me clear that, while agreeing with Lucretius as to the evils wrought in the name of religion, Oioero wished to make it plain to all men that these evils did not fiow from religion rightly understood, but from its corruption, which he distinguished by the name of superstitio ,· and that an indiscrimi- nate ettaok on all that went under the name of religion was even more injurious to society than superstition itsels.
